{{Japanese name|Maekawa}}
{{Infobox Officeholder |name = Haruo Maekawa |native_name = {{nobold|前川 春雄}} |image = Haruo Maekawa BOJ24.jpg |caption = |office = 24th [[Bank of Japan|Governor of the Bank of Japan]] |term_start = 17 December 1979 |term_end = 16 December 1984 |predecessor = [[Teiichiro Morinaga]] |successor = [[Satoshi Sumita]] |birth_date = {{birth date|1911|2|6}} |birth_place = [[Tokyo Prefecture|Tokyo]], [[Empire of Japan|Japan]] |death_date = {{death date and age|1989|9|22|1911|2|6}} |death_place = |alma_mater = [[University of Tokyo|Tokyo Imperial University]] }}
{{nihongo|'''Haruo Maekawa'''|前川 春雄|Maekawa Haruo|February 6, 1911 &ndash; September 22, 1989}}, also romanized as Mayekawa,<ref name="governors">BOJ, [http://www.boj.or.jp/en/about/outline/history/pre_gov/index.htm/ List of Governors]</ref> was a [[Japanese people|Japanese]] businessman, central banker, the 24th Governor of the [[Bank of Japan]] (BOJ).
==Early life== Maekawa was born in Tokyo.<ref>Bank of Japan (BOJ), [http://www.boj.or.jp/en/about/outline/history/pre_gov/sousai24.htm/ 24th Governor]</ref>
==Career== Before rising to become head of the Bank of Japan, Maekawa held other bank positions, including director of foreign-exchange operations.<ref>Farnsworth, Clyde H. [https://www.nytimes.com/1968/12/09/archives/central-bankers-discuss-currency-study-ways-of-neutralizing-hot.html?sq=Haruo%2520Maekawa&scp=10&st=cse "Central Bankers Discuss Currency,"] ''New York Times.'' December 9, 1968; retrieved 2011-08-17</ref>
Maekawa was Governor of the Bank of Japan from December 17, 1979 through December 16, 1984,<ref name="governors"/> having previously served as Deputy Governor from 1974 to 1979.<ref>Werner, Richard A. (2003). {{Google books|bHLC7VOc9JoC|''Princes of the Yen: Japan's Central Bankers and the Transformation of the Economy,'' p. 147|page=147}}</ref> Along with [[Minister of Finance (Japan)|Finance Minister]] [[Noboru Takeshita]], he was credited with negotiating a Saudi-Japan petrodollar accord in 1980.<ref>Ofusa, Junnosuke. [https://www.nytimes.com/1980/04/25/archives/saudijapan-petrodollar-accord-set-reports-of-iranian-fund-shifts.html?sq=Haruo%2520Maekawa&scp=11&st=cse "Saudi-Japan Petrodollar Accord Set,"] ''New York Times.'' April 25, 1980; retrieved 2011-0817</ref>
In 1986, the Maekawa Commission (the "Advisory Group on Economic Restructuring" headed by Maekawa)<ref>Library of Congress (LOC), [http://errol.oclc.org/laf/no97-12751.html Maekawa, Haruo]</ref> proposed economic reforms designed to make the living standards of Japanese more comparable to levels enjoyed in the West.<ref>Sterngold, James. [https://www.nytimes.com/1991/02/25/business/tokyo-s-importing-more-but-who-s-benefiting.html?scp=1&sq=Haruo%20Maekawa&st=cse&pagewanted=1 "Tokyo's Importing More, but Who's Benefiting?"] ''New York Times.'' February 25, 1991; [https://www.nytimes.com/1992/08/15/business/japan-s-broken-pledge-of-change-comes-back-to-haunt-its-economy.html?scp=2&sq=Haruo%20Maekawa&st=cse "Japan's Broken Pledge of Change Comes Back to Haunt Its Economy,"] ''New York Times.'' August 15, 1992; retrieved 2011-08-17</ref> Maekawa is credited as the chief author of the commission report.<ref>[http://www.oclc.org/research/activities/identities/default.htm WorldCat Identities]: [http://www.worldcat.org/identities/lccn-no97-12751 Maekawa, Haruo]; [http://www.worldcat.org/identities/np-mayekawa,%20haruo Mayekawa, Haruo ]</ref>
