{{Infobox NRHP | name =Morgan--Bedinger--Dandridge House | nrhp_type = cp | nocat = yes | image = Morgan-Bedinger-Dandridge-House rosebrake.jpg | caption = | nearest_city= [[Shepherdstown, West Virginia]] | coordinates = {{coord|39|25|37|N|77|48|43|W|display=inline,title}} | locmapin = West Virginia#USA | area = | architect= | architecture= Classical Revival, Georgian | added = May 13, 1983 | governing_body = Private | refnum=83003239 <ref name="nris">{{NRISref|2008a}}</ref> }}
The '''Morgan-Bedinger-Dandridge House''' — first known as '''Poplar Grove''', then '''Rosebrake''' — is part of a group of structures affiliated with the [[Morgan's Grove]] rural historic district near [[Shepherdstown, West Virginia]]. The property was known as "Poplar Grove" until 1877.
==History== The original building on the site was built around 1745 by settler Richard Morgan (''ca.'' 1700-1763) and became known as the "Back Building". In 1803 the house was expanded by Daniel Morgan with a two-story brick structure, known as the "Great House". Formal gardens were added at this time.
In 1859 the present main portion of the house was built by Caroline Bedinger, widow of [[Henry Bedinger]]. During her ownership the house was occupied by Colonel [[Alexander R. Boteler]], a former [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] who, at the outbreak of the [[American Civil War]] became a [[Confederate States of America|Confederate]] officer. After the war, while Boteler was living at Poplar Grove, President [[Ulysses S. Grant|U.S. Grant]] appointed Boteler to the U. S. Centennial Commission. Caroline's daughter, [[Danske Dandridge|Danske Bedinger Dandridge]], a noted poet, changed the name of the house to "Rosebrake" in 1877.
A [[portico]] was added to the house in 1950, removed from a house on [[Long Island]] and shipped to West Virginia.<ref name="nrhpinv2">{{Cite journal|title=National Register of Historic Places Nomination: Morgan-Bedinger-Dandridge House|url=http://www.wvculture.org/shpo/nr/pdf/jefferson/83003239.pdf |format=pdf|date=March 28, 1983 |author=Michael J. Pauley|publisher=National Park Service<!--None-->}} </ref>
